  <div class="main-content">
    <h2>Jesus and Nicodemus (John 3:1-15)</h2>

    <div class="section-summary">
      <p>
        Nicodemus, a Pharisee and member of the Jewish ruling council, comes to Jesus at night.
        Jesus immediately addresses his deepest need by declaring that {{ scripture("John 3:3", "no
        one can see the kingdom of God unless they are born again") }}. When Nicodemus struggles to
        understand, Jesus explains that spiritual birth comes through {{ scripture("John 3:5",
        "water and the Spirit") }}.
      </p>

      {{ theologicalTheme("Born Again (Regeneration)", "Spiritual rebirth is necessary for salvation
      and is a work of the Holy Spirit that gives new spiritual life", ["John 3:3", "John 3:5", "2
      Corinthians 5:17", "Titus 3:5"]) }}

      <p>
        Jesus uses the analogy of {{ scripture("John 3:8", "the wind blowing where it pleases") }}
        to describe the mysterious work of the Spirit in regeneration. He then points to the Old
        Testament account of {{ scripture("Numbers 21:9", "Moses lifting up the bronze serpent") }}
        as a type of His own crucifixion ({{ scripture("John 3:14-15") }}).
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>God's Love for the World (John 3:16-21)</h2>

    {{ scriptureBlock("John 3:16", "For God so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son,
    that whoever believes in him shall not perish but have eternal life.") }}

    <div class="section-summary">
      <p>This verse encapsulates the entire gospel message. It reveals:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>God's Love:</strong> The motivation for salvation</li>
        <li><strong>God's Gift:</strong> His Son as the sacrifice</li>
        <li><strong>Our Response:</strong> Believing in Jesus</li>
        <li><strong>The Result:</strong> Eternal life instead of perishing</li>
      </ul>

      {{ gospelConnection("John 3:16", "This verse summarizes the gospel: God's love, Christ's
      sacrifice, faith's response, and eternal life's promise", "1 John 4:9-10") }}

      <p>
        Jesus continues by explaining that {{ scripture("John 3:17", "God did not send his Son to
        condemn the world, but to save it") }}. However, {{ scripture("John 3:18", "those who don't
        believe are condemned already") }} because they reject the light that has come into the
        world ({{ scripture("John 3:19-21") }}).
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>John the Baptist's Final Testimony (John 3:22-36)</h2>

    <div class="section-summary">
      <p>
        When John the Baptist's disciples express concern about Jesus' growing ministry, John
        responds with joy, saying {{ scripture("John 3:30", "He must increase, but I must decrease")
        }}. This marks John's final testimony about Christ in this Gospel.
      </p>

      <p>
        The chapter concludes with a profound declaration about Christ's authority: {{
        scripture("John 3:35", "The Father loves the Son and has placed everything in his hands")
        }}. This leads to the final promise and warning: {{ scripture("John 3:36") }}.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

